abstract.title: Abstract
Background:
abstract.p: Research utilizationutilisation in clinical decision-making practice is crucial to enhance quality health carehealthcare, professional development and cost-effective health service. Nurses and midwives have a vital role in research utilizationutilisation. However, many factors influence the research utilizationutilisation ofof nurses and midwives.
abstract.title: Objectives:
abstract.p: To determine research utilizationutilisation and identify factors that affect research utilizationutilisation among nurses and midwives.
abstract.title: Methods:
abstract.p: An Iinstitutional -based, cross-sectional study design was conducted for this study from 23 May 23 to 30 June 30, 2019. A total of 631 nurses and midwives participated in the study. In addition, cCategorical variables were coded with dummy variables, and multiple linear regression model was carried out. The level of significance was set at p- value less than or equal to 0.05 with 95% confidence intervalCI.
abstract.title: Results:
abstract.p: Participants’ The total mean score in ofthe research utilizationutilisation scale score of participants was 2.27 (SD ±0.77) and their mean age of participants was 28.41 (SD ±4.71) years. ThisThe study revealed that 70.4% (444) of participants had poor research utilizationutilisation. Self-efficacy inof research utilizationutilisation skills (B=0.86, 95% CI= 0.75– to 0.97), support for research utilizationutilisation (B=0.4, 95% CI= 0.25– to 0.55) , attitude (B=0.23, 95% CI= 0.07– to 0.38), barriers ofto research utilizationutilisation (B=−0.63, 95% CI= −0.72– to −0.54), nursing/midwifery work index (B=0.07, 95% CI= 0.04– to 0.11) and hospital’s level of healthcare (B=4.5, 95% CI= 2.13– to 6.9) were statistically significantly associated factors ofof research utilizationutilisation.
abstract.title: Conclusions:
abstract.p: This study revealed that poor research utilizationutilisation ofamong nurses and midwives was poor. Barriers ofto research utilizationutilisation, supporting factors for research utilizationutilisation, attitude, self-efficacy ofin research utilizationutilisation skills, hospital’s level of healthcare and nursing/midwifery work index were found to be statistically significant predictors of research utilizationutilisation. The most common barriers ofto research utilizationutilisation were insufficient time and inability to understand statistical terms used in research articles.

body.title: Background
body.p: Research utilizationutilisation is defined as the integration of clinical expertise with the best currently available research evidence or external evidence from systematic research.1 Research utilizationutilisation in clinical decision-making practices practice ishas been increasing nowadays. There is a growing knowledge, skills and attitude ofamong nurses and midwives throughout the international community. Nurses and midwives are responsible for their profession all the way around their health carehealthcare services inusing the best available research findings in their professions.2 3 Research utilizationutilisation is considered asto playing a vital role forin the provision of quality health carehealthcare and patient safety management in the health facilities.3 National and international organizationsorganisations have been encouraging proper utilizationutilisation of research foramong quality health carehealthcare professionals. Research utilizationutilisation also increases knowledge in formal and informal health information, the expectationanticipation of a new treatment, and the role of patientspatient role related in to clinical decision-making practices.4 However, research utilizationutilisation in clinical decision-making is one of the challenges that nurses and midwives facemaking practices. utilizationutilisation are organizationalorganisational barriers ofto research utilizationutilisation.9–11 Individual categories of barriers to research utilisation includewere perception, knowledge, Capacity building of knowledge, skills and attitude of nurses and midwives16 17 is acknowledged in most countries to overcome factors that affect research utilizationutilisation in clinical decision-making practices.14 16 18 19 Although different studies were conducted on barriers ofto research utilizationutilisation have been conducted, there is no definite solution and sustainable research utilizationutilisation.3 13 Robust and visible academic leadership, organizationalorganisational demands and supportive infrastructures are necessary for capacity building and research utilizationutilisation.19 20 Therefore, nurses and midwives must lead in translating their knowledge into practice to develop quality and safe health-carehealthcare practices.21 The development of knowledge and skills of nurses and midwives as a result of the clinical and academic cooperative network has an inherent power to increase quality of health carehealthcare through research utilizationutilisation.17 20 Incorporating new knowledge is invaluable and it is a form of learning centercentre.22 Thus, organizationalorganisational context plays a significant roles toin improvinge research utilizationutilisation of nurses and midwives.23

The knowledge, skills and attitude of nurses and midwives and the context-related factors of research utilizationutilisation have beenare less studied in Ethiopia. A few validated questionnaires were used forby the studies conducted in this country, and. ElementsMoreover, elements need to be identified asthat are specific to thea particular context of research utilizationutilisation need to be identifiedin the study setting.13 The study findings will provide an opportunity to identify factors that affect research utilizationutilisation based on the context of the study setting. The results will also be served as a baseline forto measureing and monitoring change in research utilizationutilisation readiness following tailored educational and organizationalorganisational interventions. Therefore, this study was designed to determine research utilizationutilisation and identify factors that affect research utilizationutilisation among nurses and midwives.
body.title: Methods
Study design and setting
body.p: A cross-sectional study was conducted from 23 May 23 to 30 June 30, 2019, among nurses and midwives working in North Gondar and West Gojjam Zone public hospitals. The two zones are administrative zones of the Amhara Region in Ethiopia. There are 17seventeen hospitals in the zones, which include. These hospitals are two2 referral hospitals (Felege Hiwot and Gondar), two2 general hospitals (Debark and Finote Selam) and thirteen13 primary hospitals (Metema, Janamora, Wogera, Aykel, Abrhajira, Delgi, Sanja, Feresbet, Burie, Merawi, Durbetie, Addis Alem and Adet). These hospitals serve more than six million people, and the Nnurses and midwives working in these seventeen17 hospitals were included in the study.
body.title: Participants
body.p: The two2 referral hospitals had 542 nurses and 129 midwives, . Thethe two2 general hospitals had 81 nurses and 35 midwives, and. The the thirteen13 primary hospitals also had 513 nurses and 91 midwives. Nurses and midwives whose educational status washolding a diploma were excluded due to the lack of research methodology and epidemiology in their curriculum of academic diploma. Those who are working in private health institutions were also excluded from the study to avoid double counting, as it is possible in case ifthat public health workers could possiblyalso work be part-timers in the private institutions. Participants who were ill and unable to respond during the study period were also excluded from the study. The sample size for this study was calculated using single population mean formula. The required sample size for this study was determined using the following assumptions:; precision level (w)=0.85, Cconfidence level=95% (Ζα/2=1.96 value) and 9.2 standard deviationsSD. Due to the lack of the a previous study, a pilot study was conducted to getobtain standard deviationSD and precision level for the study area. Therefore, tThe calculated total sample size was 382.78. Considering thea design effect of 1.5, the sample size was 574, and adding 10% non-response rate, and the final sample size was 631.

The list of all nurses and midwives from each public hospital whose educational status waswho were bachelor’s degree and master’s degree holders in each public hospital was used as a sampling frame to identify potential study participants. In terms of research utilizationutilisation, nurses and midwives working in the same hospital were homogeneous. and sStudy participants were recruited using record identification numbers retrieved from the sampling frame. First, a proportionate stratified sampling technique was deployed to select participants from all public hospitals equally. Second, to select samples, a simple random sampling technique was conducted using the lottery method based on the proportion of the number of nurses and midwives working in each hospital to select the samples.
body.title: Instrument
body.p: All questionnaires were developed following detailed literature examination. Valid and reliable instruments were considered from different literature. Questionnaires were first prepared first in English and then translated to Amharic, which is the colloquial or mother tongue language language of the respondents. Questionnaires were also retranslated back to English for consistency. Different items used forto measureing research utilizationutilisation, attitude towards research utilizationutilisation, self--efficacy inof research utilizationutilisation skills, supporting factors for research utilizationutilisation, barriers ofto research utilizationutilisation, and nurses /midwives work index were considered. body.title: Outcome variable
body.p: The outcome variable is research utilizationutilisation, which is also considered and it isa composite variable. Eighteen statements were developed by Gerrish et al,24 andwhile the eEvidence-bBased pPractice iImplementation sScale was developed by Melnyk et aland Fineout–Overholt.25 These questionnaires were used to assess the research utilizationutilisation of respondents on a 5-point frequency scale, by indicating how often in the past eight8 weeks nurses and midwives performed each item ofon the questionnaire. Questionnaires are related to actual research utilizationutilisation,, for example, how often do you use research towards each question? Oor, ‘“use research findings to change your clinical practice’”. The responses for the alternatives were 1=never ((1one1 time before eight8the eighth week)), 2=rarely (1–3 times), 3=sometimes (4–6 times), 4=often (7–8 times) and 5=always (greater than >88eight times), with the . body.p: The questionnaire about the The independent variables related questionnaires hadcontains the following sub-sections: of socio-demographic, organisationzation-related characteristics, self-efficacy ofin research utilizationutilisation skills, attitude towards research utilizationutilisation, nursing/midwifery work index, barriers ofto research utilizationutilisation and supporting factors for research utilizationutilisation. Questions about Theaattitude, barriers ofto research utilizationutilisation, supporting factors for research utilizationutilisation and nursing / midwifery work index related items were all answered aswith the following options: strongly agree, agree, neither agree nor disagree, disagree, and strongly disagree (on a five5-point Likert scale).26 27 There are 31 questionsnaires that to assess the nursing / midwifery work index, with scores ranging froman interval of 31 to to 155. The questionnaire on Ssupporting factors for research utilizationutilisation related questionnaires contains six questions, with the total scale score ranging from 6 to 30. Five -point responses were scored from 1 to 5 and the mean scores were calculated. The mMean scores below 3, 3–4 and above four4 were considered as poor (unfavorableunfavourable), moderate and desirable, respectively.27
body.title: Data collection
body.p: Data were collected via face- to- face interview techniques using semi- structured questionnaires. Senior nurses and midwives, who had experience in data collection, participated in data collection and they had previous experience of data collection. Training in research of 4 days’ duration had beenwas given forto six data collectors and four supervisors. ItThe training focused on obtaining consent, maintaining neutrality, privacy issues, personal relation, ethics and the questionnaire content to ensure consistency of data. The pre-test was carried out before the actual data collection period among 64 (10%) of nurses and midwives working in Debre Tabor General Hospital. Based on the results of the pre-test, items on the questionnaires corrections ofthat create confusion were madecorrected before the actual data collection time. The content validity and internal reliability of each sub-section of the questionnaires were assessed using Cronbach’s alpha coefficient. The Cronbach’s alpha of the different sections of the questionnaires was between 0.7 and 0.94. The filled questionnaires were checked daily for completeness and consistency of the responses to eliminate possible errors.
body.title: Statistical analysis
body.p: The investigators and supervisors coded and checked the data manually for completeness. Data were entered into EpiData version V.3.1 and then exported to SPSS version V.20 for statistical analysis. Descriptive statistics waswere used to present frequency tables of categorical variables, and the continuous variables were presented as descriptive measures, expressed as mean and standard deviationSD. Cronbach’s alpha was used to measure reliability, mean, standard deviationSD and inter-item correlation of factors. A principal components analysis was employed to identify significant variables that explain the total variance of the factor. Categorical variables were coded with dummy variables. Bivariate analysis was used to identify correlations between variables. Multiple linear regression model was carried out and the level of significance was set at a p- value equal to or less than 0.05 with 95% confidence intervalCI to identify the effects of socio-demographic, attitude, self-efficacy ofin research utilizationutilisation skills, barriers ofto research utilizationutilisation, supporting factors for research utilizationutilisation, nursing / midwifery work index and organizationalorganisational -related factors onon research utilizationutilisation. Independence, homoscedasticity, normality and linearity were checked using Durbin-Watson, through an association between residuals and typified prognosis, using a histogram of typified residuals and partial regression graph, respectively.

body.title: Factors associated with research utilisationzation
body.p: The correlation coefficient between research utilizationutilisation, and self-efficacy ofin research utilizationutilisation skills, attitude of participants towards RUresearch utilisation, supporting factors for RUresearch utilisation, barriers ofto RUresearch utilisation, nursing/midwifery work index, position of nurses and midwives, marital status, adequate number of staffs, nursing/midwifery work index and hospital’s level of healthcare in the bivariate analysis ranged from was −0.726 to −0.05 and from 0.08 to 0.73. Significant correlation was found at a Pp- value of 0.01. Self-efficacy ofin research utilisationRU skills, attitude of participants towards RUresearch utilisation, barriers ofto RUresearch utilisation, supporting factors for RUresearch utilisation, hospital’s level of healthcare and nursing / midwifery work index were found to be correlated with the outcome variable in the bivariate analysis and had statistically significant association with research utilizationutilisation.

This study found that the research utilizationutilisation scale score increased when the self-efficacy ofin research utilisationRU skills scale score (B=0.86, 95% CI= 0.75– to 0.97), attitude of participants towards research utilisationRU scale score (B=0.23, 95% CI= 0.07– to 0.38), supporting factors for research utilisationRU scale score (B=0.4, 95% CI= 0.25– to 0.55) and nursing/midwifery work index scale score (B=0.07, 95% CI= 0.04– to 0.11) of participants were increased. However, research utilisationRU scale score decreased when the barriers of to research utilisationRU scale score (B=−0.63, 95% CI= −0.72– to −0.54) increased. The research utilizationutilisation scale score of nurses and midwives working in specializedspecialised hospitals (B=4.5, 95% CI= 2.13– to 6.9) was greaterhigher than the research utilizationutilisation score of nurses and midwives working in general and primary hospitals (see see table 7). Moreover, factor analysis indicated that beliefve of research-based practice and trusted study findings increased research utilizationutilisation among nurses and midwives. The support pofrovided by nursing and midwifery managers who embrace research -based practice and the self-efficacy of in research utilisationRU skills ofin identifying clinical problems according to currently available research findings also increased research utilizationutilisation. ButHowever, difficulty in finding time to search for and read research articles and reports, andas well as inability to understand statistical terms used in research articles were found to be barriers ofto research utilizationutilisation.
body.title: Discussion
body.p: The results of this study showed thatpoor research utilizationutilisation ofamong nurses and midwives was poor. ButHowever, there were encouraging activities of nurses and midwives to use research in clinical decision- making practice. For example, participants informally discussed a research articles to use as evidence for clinical decision-making practice. They also use internet to search for research articles in order to make clinical decisions. Similarly, other studies in Sweden, Norway, Turkey and cChina have showned that there waslow research utilizationutilisation7 28–30 due to the possibileity of lack of information onf research utilizationutilisation and the lack of commitment to use research. ThisThe findings of poor research utilizationutilisation finding could be explained as thereby wasthe lack of support to apply the the knowledge of nurses and midwives throughby reducing barriers ofto research utilizationutilisation in healthcare. However, the findings of this study showed that about 29%twenty-nine and less than 1%one percent of the participants engaged in using research iforn decision–-making practice ofin healthcare moderately and desirably, respectively. As the research findings have indicated, it was the effort of some nurses and midwives to use research without getting support from concerned bodies. The Rresearch utilizationutilisation score of nurses was higher than the the research utilisationRU score of midwives. This could be due to the lack of knowledge and skills to use research in the clinical practice, and the inadequate staffs among midwives in the study settings compared tocompared with nurses.

Self-efficacy ofin research utilizationutilisation skills was important toin increaseing research utilizationutilisation forin decision-making practice in the healthcare service. Although participants’ self-efficacy ofin research utilizationutilisation skills of participants was poor, the research utilizationutilisation scale score increased when self-efficacy ofin research utilisationRU skills scale scoreincreased. The study found that participants had hopeful activities likesuch as identifying clinical problems according to currently available research findings and reading a research reports. They have a general notion about the strengths and weaknesses of articles. The results of this study coincided with the findings of studies reported in Sweden, Norway, Singapore and Ethiopia.8 31–33 This might be due to the similarity ofin the support offor self-efficacy ofin research utilisationRU skills of the participants in the study settings. The poor self-efficacy ofin research utilizationutilisation skills may be thea result of nurses’ and midwives’ incompetency to perform their task usingaccording to research. The results of this study revealed that nurses and midwives had moderately positive attitude towards RUresearch utilisation;, buthowever, the participants use research in clinical practice to a smalllesser extent. Research utilizationutilisation scale score was higher among those who had higher attitudes scale score. This finding coincided with the studies conducted in Norway, Singapore, Sweden, China, Iran and Nigeria.5 29 32–35 This could be because ofdue to the positive attitude of nurses and midwives that encourage participants of the study settingsthem to use research. Positive attitude towards research utilizationutilisation could be vital to engage nurses and midwives in research utilizationutilisation activities. If nurses and midwives do not believe in the value of research, research utilizationutilisation can be difficult. At the same time, the poor attitude towards research utilizationutilisation indicated in this study might be due to poor self-efficacy ofin research utilizationutilisation skills.

The findings of this study revealed that when barriers ofto research utilisationRU scale score increased, research utilizationutilisation scale score decreased. Difficulty in finding time to search for and read research reports andas well as inability to understand statistical terms used in research articles were the top barriers ofto research utilizationutilisation. ThisThese findings isare in line with the reports of studies in Singapore, Oman, Norway, Turkey and Iran.14 27 28 33 36 This is because ofdue to work overload, lack of training ofin research utilizationutilisation and lack of awareness of nurses and midwives to use research findings in clinical decision-making practices practice. The findings of this study showed that majority of the participants had moderate or desirable barriers ofto research utilizationutilisation. Different factors likesuch as lack of resources, judging the quality of research and other factors had contribution tocontributed to barriers ofto research utilizationutilisation. In order to reduce research utilizationutilisation, overcoming all components which result in unsuccessful research utilizationutilisation is vital. In terms of gender, the score offor barriers ofto research utilisationRU among female nurses and midwives was greaterhigher than among male nurses and midwives. This may be because ofdue to overlapping activities and lack of attention to support female nurses and midwives. A Hhigher score ofin barriers ofto research utilisation RU was identified among nurses and midwives whose year of experience waswith 11–34 years of experience. This could be explained by as: theyoung nurses and midwives’ capabilityies, which reduce barriers ofto research utilisation RU because ofdue to their recent university experience.

The findings of this study revealed that supporting factors for research utilizationutilisation scale score increased research utilisationRU scale score. Nursing and midwifery manager’s embracing research -based practice was the most important activity that increased research utilisationRU scale score. Similarly, other studies revealed that support offor research utilizationutilisation ofamong nurses and midwives had improved many activities related to research utilisationRU and quality health carehealthcare.31 32 37 Lack of access to a system, and lack of training and mentoring were also contributing factors ofto poor support for research utilizationutilisation. Training and mentoring of nurses and midwivescan provide support to nurses and midwives to use valid and reliable literature within clinical settings and familiarizefamiliarise nurses and midwivesthem with to the Cochrane Library. Therefore, it is crucial to focus on the skills and knowledge of managers toin providing support for research utilizationutilisation. In relationterms to the result of supporting factors for RUresearch utilisation, higher scores obtained among male nurses and midwives obtained higher scores. Perhaps, male empowerment to get support for research utilisationRU was better than females’ empowerment and that priority was given for malesto men.

Research utilizationutilisation scale score increased among ofnurses and midwives increased for those who had higher nursing / midwifery work index scale score than nurses and midwivesthose who had lower nursing/ midwifery work index scale score. This finding is supported by thea study finding reported in Spain.38 This could be explained by respondents who hadwith better nursing /midwifery work index score could havinge the motivation to use research in clinical decision-making practice. Different factors contributed forto poor nursing and midwifery work index. Creating good working environment and job satisfaction were important to research utilizationutilisation throughby improving nursing and midwifery work index.

Research utilizationutilisation scale score of nurses and midwives working in specializedspecialised hospitals was higher than research utilizationutilisation scale score of nurses and midwives working in general and primary hospitals. The study findings reported by a study in Egypt also revealed that research utilizationutilisation varies in different study settings.39 This could be due to involvement of academic staffs toin usinge research in clinical decision-making practice in specializedspecialised hospitals, as well as andthe encouraging factors of research utilizationutilisation in the specializedspecialised hospitals of this study and the Assiut University Hospital in Egypt. The specializedspecialised hospitals were teaching hospitals which had adequate resources, training opportunities and the staffs with the highest level of educational status to use research.
body.title: The sStrengths and limitations
body.p: The major strength of this study was the use of face-to-face interview techniques,s which contributed for theto the 100% response rate of hundred percent. The rRisk of bias was reduced restricted throughby ensuring the privacy forof the interviewees. This study addresses that research utilizationutilisation which in this study is typically underpinnedsupported throughby decreasing barriers ofto research utilizationutilisation, and increasingimproving self-efficacy ofin research utilizationutilisation skills, increasing support for research utilizationutilisation, positive attitude towards research utilizationutilisation, nursing/ midwifery work index and hospital’s level of healthcare. As far as our search for studies conducted in Ethiopia, this is the first study in Ethiopiathe country to use validated instrument to assess nurses’ and midwives’ attitude, self -efficacy ofin research utilizationutilisation skills, barriers ofto research utilizationutilisation, supporting factors for research utilizationutilisation, nursing /midwifery work index and research utilizationutilisation.

The first limitation of this study was the possibility forof social desirability bias as the study was conducted while nurses and midwives were working in the hospitals. Moreover, the response of the participants might be inflated or underestimated due to individuals with some interests. Second, this study was conducted in hospitals where more advanced human resource dynamics, quality medical service and well organizationalorganisational structure were available. Hence, it is difficult to generalizegeneralise forto health centerscentres and health posts. Finally, thea limitation of this cross-sectional study was that qualitative studydesign was not mixedused to strengthen the findings of this cross-section study.
body.title: Conclusions
body.p: This study revealed that research utilizationutilisation was poor. Self-efficacy ofin RUresearch utilisation skills, supporting factors for RUresearch utilisation, attitude towards RUresearch utilisation, barriers ofto research utilisation RU, nursing/midwifery work index and level of hospitals were found to be statistically significant predictors of research utilizationutilisation. Insufficienttable 7 time to read research and inability to understand statistical terms used in research articles are the most common barriers ofto research utilizationutilisation.
